1. Rolling Deployments
    - How it works:
        Replace old instances with new instances one by one.
        Traffic is automatically routed to healthy instances.
        Old version is still partially running until new version is fully deployed.
    - Node.js Example:
        Suppose you run a Node.js API on 3 servers.
        Server 1 updates first → traffic is routed to Server 2 and 3.
        Server 2 updates next → traffic continues to the updated servers.
        Finally, Server 3 updates → now all servers run the new version.
    - Pros: No downtime.
    - Cons: Hard to rollback quickly if something goes wrong.

2. Blue/Green Deployments
    - Goal: Switch users instantly between two environments.
    - How it works:
        Blue environment: current production version.
        Green environment: new version being prepared.
        Switch traffic from blue → green once ready.
    - Node.js Example:
        Deploy Node.js app version 1.0 to blue servers.
        Deploy Node.js app version 1.1 to green servers.
        Run smoke tests on green.
        Change load balancer to route all users to green.
        Blue version can stay as backup.
    - Pros: Instant rollback, zero downtime.
    - Cons: Requires double infrastructure.

3. Canary Deployments
    - Goal: Test new version on a small percentage of users first.
    - How it works:
        Deploy new version to 5–10% of servers/users.
        Monitor logs and metrics.
        Gradually increase traffic to new version if no issues.
    - Node.js Example:
        Version 2.0 of Node.js API is deployed to one server in a 10-server cluster.
        Only 10% of user requests hit the new server.
        If everything is fine → expand to 50%, then 100%.
    - Pros: Limits risk of new bugs affecting all users.
    - Cons: Slightly more complex traffic routing.

4. Feature Flags Integration
    - Goal: Ship code with hidden features and enable them selectively.
    - How it works:
        Code contains all features but flags control what is active.
        Flags can be toggled at runtime without redeploying.
    - Node.js Example:
        const featureFlags = {
            newPaymentFlow: false
        };
        app.post("/pay", (req, res) => {
            if (featureFlags.newPaymentFlow) {
                return res.send("New payment flow active");
            } else {
                return res.send("Old payment flow");
            }
        });
        Deploy app with newPaymentFlow: false.
        Enable flag for 5% of users → test behavior.
        Turn on for everyone after confirmation.
    - Pros: Safe experimentation and A/B testing.
    - Cons: Code complexity can increase.

5. Infrastructure as Code (IaC) Integration:
    - Infrastructure as Code (IaC) means you define and manage your infrastructure—servers, databases, networks, cloud resources—using code instead of manual setup. This makes deployments repeatable, version-controlled, and automatable.
    - Integrating IaC into CI/CD ensures your application and its infrastructure are deployed together in a fully automated, consistent manner.

6. Provision and Deploy Environments:
    - Definition: Create and configure infrastructure automatically using IaC tools rather than manually clicking in the cloud console.
    - Popular IaC Tools:
        Terraform – cloud-agnostic, declarative infrastructure definitions
        Ansible – configuration management and provisioning
        Pulumi – use programming languages (JS, TS, Python) to define infrastructure
    - Example with Terraform (Node.js app deployed to AWS EC2):
        # main.tf
        provider "aws" {
            region = "us-east-1"
        }
        resource "aws_instance" "node_app" {
            ami           = "ami-0c55b159cbfafe1f0"
            instance_type = "t2.micro"
            tags = {
                Name = "NodeAppServer"
            }
            provisioner "remote-exec" {
                inline = [
                "sudo apt-get update -y",
                "sudo apt-get install -y nodejs npm",
                "git clone https://github.com/username/node-app.git /home/ubuntu/node-app",
                "cd /home/ubuntu/node-app && npm install && npm start"
                ]
            }
        }
    - Explanation:
        - This Terraform script creates an EC2 instance and deploys your Node.js app automatically.
        - No manual provisioning needed.

7. Integrate IaC in Pipelines:
    - Definition: Embed IaC execution into your CI/CD pipeline so that deploying infrastructure and code happens automatically together.
    - Example: GitHub Actions pipeline with Terraform for Node.js app:
        name: Node.js CI/CD with Terraform
        on: [push]
        jobs:
            build-and-test:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                steps:
                    - uses: actions/checkout@v3
                    - uses: actions/setup-node@v3
                        with:
                        node-version: 18
                    - run: npm install
                    - run: npm test
            deploy-infra:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                needs: build-and-test
                steps:
                    - uses: actions/checkout@v3
                    - name: Setup Terraform
                        uses: hashicorp/setup-terraform@v2
                        with:
                            terraform_version: 1.6.0
                    - name: Terraform Init
                        run: terraform init
                    - name: Terraform Apply
                        run: terraform apply -auto-approve
                        env:
                            AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID: ${{ secrets.AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID }}
                            AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY: ${{ secrets.AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY }}
    - Explanation:
        - build-and-test job runs Node.js tests first.
        - deploy-infra job runs Terraform to provision infrastructure.
        - Secrets for AWS credentials are stored securely in GitHub Secrets.
        - If tests fail, the pipeline stops and does not deploy, ensuring safety.

8. Key Benefits of IaC Integration in CI/CD
    Benefit	        Explanation
    Consistency	    Every environment (dev, staging, prod) is deployed the same way.
    Version Control	Infrastructure changes are tracked in Git repositories.
    Automation	    No manual provisioning—pipeline provisions and deploys automatically.
    Safety	        Combined with tests and policies, prevents deploying broken or misconfigured infrastructure.